{"ts": "2026-06-08T23:49:42.643041+00:00", "update": {"model": {"messages": [{"type": "ai", "data": {"content": "Here's a summary of the module structure of this Spring Boot template project:\n\n---\n\n## Module Structure Overview\n\nThis is a **multi-module Gradle project** named `spring-boot-java-template`. It follows a layered architecture where modules are grouped by responsibility. All modules live under a root Gradle project and share dependency versions managed centrally via `gradle.properties`.\n\n### 1. **`core`** — Core Business Logic\nThe heart of the application, where each submodule represents a domain service.\n\n- **`core:core-api`** — The **only executable module** (has `bootJar.enabled = true`). It is the Spring Boot application entry point. It depends on all other modules and wires them together. It exposes REST APIs and sets up the framework for services. Dependencies: `spring-boot-starter-webmvc`, plus all other project modules.\n\n- **`core:core-enum`** — A lightweight library module (empty `build.gradle`, no extra dependencies). It holds **shared enumerations** used by `core-api` and potentially exposed to external consumers. No dependencies on other project modules — it's the leaf of the dependency tree.\n\n### 2. **`clients`** — External System Integration\nModules here handle outbound communication with external services.\n\n- **`clients:client-example`** — A reference implementation showing how to integrate with external HTTP APIs using **Spring Cloud OpenFeign** (with Apache HC5 and Micrometer metrics support). Serves as a template for building additional Feign clients.\n\n### 3. **`storage`** — Data Persistence\nModules here encapsulate database and storage access.\n\n- **`storage:db-core`** — Demonstrates database access using **Spring Data JPA** with **MySQL** as the primary runtime database and **H2** available for testing. It depends on `core:core-enum` (for shared domain enums used in entities).\n\n### 4. **`support`** — Cross-Cutting Concerns\nInfrastructure and operational support modules.\n\n- **`support:logging`** — Provides **logging and distributed tracing** support. Dependencies: `spring-boot-starter-opentelemetry` (OpenTelemetry tracing) and `sentry-logback` (error reporting to Sentry).\n\n- **`support:monitoring`** — Provides **application monitoring and metrics**. Dependencies: `spring-boot-starter-actuator` (health checks, metrics endpoints) and `micrometer-registry-prometheus` (Prometheus metrics export).\n\n### 5. **`tests`** — Testing Utilities\nModules here support the testing workflow.\n\n- **`tests:api-docs`** — A convenience module for writing **Spring REST Docs** tests (Asciidoc-based API documentation generation from test output). Used as a test dependency by `core-api`.\n\n---\n\n## Dependency Graph (simplified)\n\n```\ncore:core-api  (the runnable app)\n  ├── core:core-enum\n  ├── support:monitoring\n  ├── support:logging\n  ├── storage:db-core\n  │     └── core:core-enum\n  ├── clients:client-example\n  └── tests:api-docs  (test only)\n```\n\n## Design Philosophy\n\nThe README makes the intent clear: this is a **pragmatic starter structure** designed to maximize early-stage development productivity. The authors explicitly note it's \"not the best structure\" but \"a good basic structure to use early in the project.\" Each module group (`core`, `clients`, `storage`, `support`, `tests`) is expected to grow with the service — new submodules get added as domains expand (e.g., new `core:*` modules for additional domain services, new `clients:*` for additional integrations, new `storage:*` for other data stores).", "additional_kwargs": {"refusal": null}, "response_metadata": {"token_usage": {"completion_tokens": 794, "prompt_tokens": 10807, "total_tokens": 11601, "completion_tokens_details": {"accepted_prediction_tokens": null, "audio_tokens": 0, "reasoning_tokens": 11, "rejected_prediction_tokens": null, "image_tokens": 0}, "prompt_tokens_details": {"audio_tokens": 0, "cached_